# TODO: black-brown coalition


@popular_front_coalition
title: A new "Popular Front" coalition?
subtitle: CCF + PCC + RPC + LPC  [? if sapd_formed: + SAPD ?]([+ popular_front_coalition +]%)
unavailable-subtitle: CCF + PCC + RPC + LPC [? if sapd_formed: + SAPD ?]([+ popular_front_coalition +]%) - [? if ((pcc_relation < 65 and pcc_party_leader == "Thälmann") or (pcc_relation < 45 and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators")): We do not have good enough relations with the PCC. ?][? if (rpc_relation < 45 and rpc_party_leader == "Joos") or (rpc_relation < 65 and rpc_party_leader != "Joos" and pcc_party_leader != "Conciliators") or (rpc_relation < 55 and rpc_party_leader != "Joos" and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators"): We do not have good enough relations with the Center Party. ?][? if communist_coalition < 3 : The Communists are unwilling to compromise at all. ?]
view-if: popular_front_coalition >= 50
choose-if: (((pcc_relation >= 65 and pcc_party_leader == "Thälmann") or (pcc_relation >= 45 and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators")) and ((rpc_relation >= 45 and rpc_party_leader == "Joos") or (rpc_relation >= 65 and rpc_party_leader != "Joos" and pcc_party_leader != "Conciliators") or (rpc_relation >= 55 and rpc_party_leader != "Joos" and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators")) and lpc_relation >= 50 and communist_coalition >= 3) or (rpc_party_leader == "Joos" and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators" and rpc_relation >= 30 and pcc_relation >= 30)

Could we really form a coalition that included both the Center and the Communists? It seems like an absurd concept, but given our good relationships with both sides, it is not an impossibility.

The far-right might attempt a coup, if such a coalition were formed.

- @popular_front_2: Form the Popular Front!
- @great_popular_front: Form the Popular Front!

@popular_front_2
view-if: rpc_party_leader != "Joos" or pcc_party_leader != "Conciliators"

Somehow, both the Communists and Center are at the very least willing to entertain negotiations. Of course, PCC radicals and Center conservatives derail the negotiations almost immediately. The PCC demands leadership of the coalition for themselves and their chairman Ernst Thälmann, [? if ccf_r > pcc_r : despite our higher vote share, ?]while the Center is offended by the prospect of helping Bolsheviks enter government. *Something* must be done to restore balance.

- @popular_front_resources
- @popular_front_democracy
- @popular_front_woodsworth
- @coalition_menu: This is impossible. Try another governing arrangement.

@popular_front_resources
title: Use our resources to smooth things over.
unavailable-subtitle: Required: 4 resources
subtitle: -4 resources
choose-if: resources >= 4
on-arrival: resources -= 4
go-to: popular_front_success

@popular_front_democracy
title: Convince the PCC to accept democracy.
subtitle: [? if pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators" : The Conciliator leadership of the PCC at least claim to support the Popular Front. ?]
unavailable-subtitle: Our relationship with the PCC is not high enough.
choose-if: (pcc_relation >= 60 and communist_coalition >= 3) or pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators"
go-to: popular_front_success

@popular_front_woodsworth
title: Use pressure from King Woodsworth to force the parties to cooperate.
view-if: king == "Woodsworth"
go-to: popular_front_success

@great_popular_front
view-if: rpc_party_leader == "Joos" and pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators"
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; in_popular_front = 1; chancellor = "Gardiner"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; pcc_relation += 10; coup_progress += 2; in_left_front = 0; in_weimar_coalition = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; coalition_dissent = 0;
achievement: grosse_volksfront
go-to: popular_front_civil_war if coup_progress >= 10; popular_front_no_civil_war if coup_progress < 10

Somehow, the coalition is successfully formed! The conciliatory leadership of the Center Party and PCC helped make the negotiations possible. We still need a chancellor; the only acceptable choice among the parties was Robert Gardiner of the CCF, acceptable to the Center and PCC [? if king == "George V" : as well as King George V, albeit extremely reluctantly ?].

@popular_front_success
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; in_popular_front = 1; chancellor = "Gardiner"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; pcc_relation += 10; coup_progress += 2; in_left_front = 0; in_weimar_coalition = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; coalition_dissent = 0;
go-to: popular_front_civil_war if coup_progress >= 10; popular_front_no_civil_war if coup_progress < 10
achievement: volksfront

Somehow, surprisingly, the coalition is successfully formed! We still need a chancellor; the only acceptable choice among the parties was Robert Gardiner of the CCF, acceptable to the Center and PCC [? if king == "George V" : as well as King George V, albeit extremely reluctantly ?].

@popular_front_no_civil_war
on-arrival: pcc_goals_seen = 0; finance_minister_party = "RPC"; interior_minister_party = "RPC"; economic_minister_party = "RPC"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; foreign_minister_party = "RPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister = "I"; leverage = ccf_r + pcc_r;
achievement: volksfront

In response to the PCC's entrance into the government, the right-wing takes a "wait-and-see" approach for now. They expect that the Popular Front government will be unstable and incompetent, and will collapse of its own accord, discrediting the left and center and eventually enabling the destruction of the Weimar Republic. Our task is to prove them wrong.

The PCC has taken an abstentionist position with regards to ministries. They claim to be participating as the "loyal opposition" within the Popular Front government, supporting us from the outside while also running their own propaganda campaigns to turn workers to their side. They seem to expect that the Popular Front would inevitably fail, and that our failure would benefit them.

- @ministries: First, we must select our ministries.


@popular_front_civil_war
on-arrival: pcc_relation = 80; reichswehr_loyalty += 0.25;

In response to the PCC's entrance into the government, the right-wing immediately launches a coup attempt. Troops of the Stahlhelm and Nazi SA enter Berlin and immediately begin clashing with our supporters! Reactionary officers within the Reichswehr have taken their troops out of the barracks and joined them with the Stahlhelm to stop us from taking power.

The Center manages to diffuse some of the hostility from the Reichswehr and the Stahlhelm, but fail to prevent the outbreak of fighting. We are forced to fight on the same side as the PCC, whether we want to or not.

- @civil_war: A civil war, then.



@far_right_coalition
title: Far-right coalition
subtitle: NSDAP + SCP ([+ far_right_coalition +]%)
view-if: far_right_coalition >= 50
go-to: far_right_win if (year >= 1932 or nsdap_r >= 44) and king != "Woodsworth"; far_right_fail if (year < 1932 and nsdap_r < 44) and king != "Woodsworth"; far_right_woodsworth if king == "Woodsworth"
priority: 2

There are enough votes for the Nazis and the SCP to form a coalition. [+ nsdap_leader +] has made his participation in government contingent on being appointed chancellor. It is up to King [+ king +] to decide.

@far_right_win
on-arrival: chancellor = nsdap_leader; chancellor_party = "NSDAP"

[? if king == "George V" : King George V's camarilla ?][? if king == "Woodsworth" : King Woodsworth somehow ?] has decided that [+ nsdap_leader +] must be chancellor [? if king == "George V": , and the aging king accepts their recommendations. ?][? if king == "Woodsworth" : because it is what the constitution would stipulate. ?]

- @hitler_takes_power: What do we do now?


@far_right_fail
on-arrival: chancellor = "Schleicher"; chancellor_party = "I"; pro_republic -= 10; next_election_time = time+5; next_election_month = month + 5; next_election_year = year; next_election_year += 1 if next_election_month > 12; next_election_month -= 12 if next_election_month > 12;

The reactionary establishment is still very skeptical of the Nazis, so instead, [+ king +] appoints Kurt von Schleicher, a former general, as chancellor, to try to "tame" the Nazis.

Schleicher's government is deeply unpopular among all parties of the Reichstag. Despite his support for a coalition with the NSDAP, the Nazis want power all to themselves, without Schleicher.

New elections have been set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].

@far_right_woodsworth
on-arrival: coup_progress += 2

King Woodsworth faces a dilemma. Is it "democratic" to let democracy be destroyed, if the majority of voters have willed it so? Some, even on the left, suggest that the Nazis would not *truly* be as horrific as their platform suggests, and that giving them power would let them discredit themselves in the eyes of the public.

Alternatively, Woodsworth could use the emergency powers of the presidency. Article 48 has been used by George V to promulgate anti-democratic and anti-worker policies; can Article 48 be used for good as well as evil?

- @emergency_woodsworth: We will form an emergency government with Woodsworth's support.
- @new_elections: We will have new elections.
- @far_right_win: Let the Nazis form their government.


@left_coalition
title: Is a United Left coalition possible?
subtitle: CCF + PCC [? if sapd_formed: + SAPD ?] ([+ left_coalition +]%)
unavailable-subtitle: CCF + PCC [? if sapd_formed: + SAPD ?] ([+ left_coalition +]%). [? if pcc_relation < 50 : We do not have adequate relations with the PCC. ?][? if communist_coalition < 3 : The Communists are too committed to their radical ways to partake in government. ?]
view-if: left_coalition >= 50
choose-if: (pcc_relation >= 50 or (pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators" and pcc_relation >= 40)) and communist_coalition >= 3

There are enough votes for a CCF + PCC coalition government, if such a thing were actually possible.

The far-right might attempt a coup, if such a coalition were formed.

- @left_coalition_impossible: This is impossible.
- @left_coalition_possible: This could be possible.

@left_coalition_impossible
go-to: coalition_menu

A far left coalition is impossible.


@left_coalition_possible

The PCC is still very reluctant to join a coalition, despite grassroots friendliness between our memberships. The Stalinist leadership is vehemently against such a thing. They demand the appointment of Ernst Thälmann as chancellor in exchange for a coalition. [? if king == "George V" : There is no chance whatsoever that King George V would approve of the appointment of a die-hard communist as chancellor. ?] Alternatively, if our relations with them are good enough, we could convince them to support the appointment of one of our centrist or left-leaning members as chancellor.

- @thalmann_chancellor: Appoint Thälmann as chancellor.
- @left_coalition_resources
- @left_coalition_relations
- @coalition_menu: Try a different governing arrangement.

@thalmann_chancellor
choose-if: king == "Woodsworth" and reformist_strength + neorevisionist_strength < left_strength
unavailable-subtitle: [? if king != "Woodsworth": King [+ king +] would never allow such a thing. ?] [? if reformist_strength >= left_strength : Most in the parliamentary party would not support Thälmann as chancellor. ?]
on-arrival: chancellor = "Thälmann"; chancellor_party = "PCC"; pcc_relation = 80; in_left_front = 1; ccf_in_government = 1 

With great reluctance, King [+ king +] appoints [+ chancellor +] as chancellor.

Immediately, [+ chancellor +] goes to work building a "Soviet Canada": consolidating as much power as possible in the PCC, purging state institutions of anti-communists, and sending street fighters against the "enemies of the people".

In response to [+ chancellor +] being appointed Chancellor, the right-wing forces launches almost immediately launch an attempted coup. Troops of the Stahlhelm and Nazi SA enter Berlin and immediately begin clashing with our supporters! Reactionary officers within the Reichswehr have taken their troops out of the barracks and joined them with the Stahlhelm to stop the PCC from taking power. We are forced to be on the same side as the PCC, whether we want to or not.

- @civil_war


@left_coalition_resources
title: Use our resources to smooth things over.
unavailable-subtitle: Required: 3 resources
subtitle: -3 resources
choose-if: resources >= 3
on-arrival: resources -= 3
go-to: left_coalition_success

@left_coalition_relations
title: Convince the PCC to accept democracy.
unavailable-subtitle: Our relationships with the PCC are not good enough.
choose-if: pcc_relation >= 60 or pcc_party_leader == "Conciliators"
go-to: left_coalition_success


@left_coalition_success
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; in_left_front = 1; chancellor = "Gardiner"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; coup_progress += 3; capital_strike_progress += 2; in_popular_front = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; in_weimar_coalition = 0; pcc_relation += 10
go-to: left_coalition_civil_war if coup_progress >= 10; left_coalition_no_civil_war if coup_progress < 10
achievement: einheitsfront

Somehow, surprisingly, the left coalition is successfully formed, without appointing Thälmann as chancellor. The consensus choice for chancellor, accepted by the CCF, PCC, and King [+ king +], is Robert Gardiner, who belongs to the centrist faction of the CCF, but was acceptable to the left due to his previous membership in the left-wing anti-war UCCF.

# just raise the coup limit, don't immediately go to civil war

@left_coalition_no_civil_war
on-arrival: pcc_goals_seen = 0; foreign_minister_party = "CCF"; interior_minister_party = "CCF"; justice_minister_party = "CCF"; labor_minister_party = "CCF"; reichswehr_minister_party = "CCF"; economic_minister_party = "CCF"; finance_minister_party = "CCF"; agriculture_minister_party = "CCF"; reichswehr_loyalty -= 0.05

In response to the PCC's entrance into the government, the right-wing takes a "wait-and-see" approach for now. They expect that our government will be unstable and incompetent, and will collapse of its own accord, discrediting the left and eventually enabling the destruction of the Weimar Republic. Our task is to prove them wrong.

The PCC has taken an abstentionist position with regards to ministries. They claim to be participating as the "loyal opposition" in the worker's government, supporting us from the outside while also running their own propaganda campaigns to turn workers to their side. They seem to expect that we would inevitably fail, and that our failure would benefit them. 

Whatever their reasoning is, the CCF has control over the ministries of government.

@left_coalition_civil_war
on-arrival: reichswehr_loyalty += 0.1

In response to the PCC's entrance into the government, the right-wing immediately launches a coup attempt. Troops of the Stahlhelm and Nazi SA enter Berlin and begin clashing with our supporters. Reactionary officers within the Reichswehr have taken their troops out of the barracks and joined them with the Stahlhelm to stop us from taking power.

- @civil_war: A civil war, then.



@right_coalition
title: Refuse to form a government, so that a right-wing coalition may be formed.
subtitle: RPC + BVP + CPC + SCP + Others ([+ right_coalition +]%)
unavailable-subtitle: The SCP is not interested in a coalition with the Center.
view-if: right_coalition >= 50
choose-if: year < 1929

There are enough votes for a right-wing coalition of the Center (+ BVP), CPC, SCP, and minor conservative parties. [? if largest_party == "CCF": However, this will be seen as abdicating responsibility for government, as we are the largest party. ?]

- @right_coalition_sure: Yes, we will abdicate our responsibility for government formation, and let a right-wing coalition take power.
- @grand_coalition: Actually, we wish to form a grand coalition after all.

@no_right_coalition
go-to: no_majority

However, the SCP and its leader Hugenberg is refusing to partake in a coalition with the "November criminals" in the Center Party. Thus, there is no clear path towards a Reichstag majority.

@right_coalition_sure
subtitle: This will be extremely unpopular within our party.
on-arrival: pro_republic -= 5; center_dissent += 15; left_dissent += 10; labor_dissent += 25; reformist_dissent += 25; neorevisionist_dissent += 15; rpc_relation -= 5; lpc_relation -= 5; cpc_relation -= 5
go-to: right_coalition_2


@right_coalition_2
unavailable-subtitle: The SCP is not interested in a coalition with the Center.
view-if: right_coalition >= 50
choose-if: year < 1929
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 0; ccf_toleration = 0; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; foreign_minister_party = "CPC"; interior_minister_party = "SCP"; justice_minister_party = "SCP"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = "CPC"; finance_minister_party = "RPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "SCP"; in_right_coalition = 1;

Even though the SCP is very reluctant to participate in such a coalition, they still accede to King George V's wishes. Thus, a majority center-right coalition is formed, with Brüning as chancellor.



@no_majority
title: There is no clear governing majority.
view-if: weimar_coalition < 50 and (grand_coalition < 50 or grand_coalition_failed == 1) and king = "George V" and far_right_coalition < 50
on-arrival: no_majority_elections += 1
go-to: no_majority_bruning if chancellor = "Brüning" or chancellor = "Wirth"; no_majority_papen if chancellor = "Papen" and no_majority_papen_elections == 0; no_majority_papen_2 if chancellor == "Papen" and no_majority_papen_elections > 0; no_majority_schleicher if chancellor = "Schleicher"; no_majority_ccf if chancellor_party = "CCF" or chancellor == "Marx"

# TODO: if there is an anti-democratic coalition majority, you should appoint Papen.

# either new elections, or George V appoints either Brüning, Papen, Schleicher, or Hitler.

@no_majority_ccf
on-arrival: chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"

There is no path to an obviously workable majority. Since King George V is unwilling to work with a minority or caretaker CCF government, his preferred chancellor is Heinrich Brüning of the Center Party, who could lead a "monarchial" government.

- @toleration_bruning: We will tolerate Brüning.
- @new_grand_coalition: We will try to form a new grand coalition.
- @new_elections: We will have new elections.

# - if NSDAP is the largest party and the 

@no_majority_bruning
go-to: no_majority_bruning_toleration if (no_majority_elections <= 3 and anti_democratic_coalition <= 50); georgev_appoints_papen if no_majority_elections > 3 or anti_democratic_coalition > 50


@georgev_appoints_papen
on-arrival: chancellor = "Papen"; chancellor_party = "I"; next_election_time = time+3; next_election_month = month + 3; next_election_year = year; next_election_year += 1 if next_election_month > 12; next_election_month -= 12 if next_election_month > 12; sa_banned = 0; pro_republic -= 8; finance_minister_party = "I"; interior_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = "I"; labor_minister_party = "I"; foreign_minister_party = "I"; agriculture_minister_party = "I"; reichswehr_minister = "I";

There is no path to a majority government. King George V is tired of the chaos, and appoints Franz von Papen as chancellor instead of Brüning. Papen is a indenpendent formerly from the Center Party, and is significantly to the right of the majority of the Center Party.

Papen is immediately faced with a vote of no confidence, given his unpopularity. However the CCF votes, he is guaranteed to fall, due to the unanimous hatred against him from all other parties.

New elections have been set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].

@no_majority_bruning_toleration
on-arrival: no_majority_bruning_elections += 1

There is no path to a majority government. One option would be to have a continuation of the current Brüning government; if we tolerate it, then it would retain a majority vote against no-confidence.

Alternatively, we could try to form a "new grand coalition" of all constitutional parties except the NSDAP, PCC, and SCP. The stumbling block are the minor conservative parties such as the "Economic Party of the Middle Class", who detest any hint of socialism and would ruin the country before working with Marxists.

The third option is to have new elections.

- @toleration_bruning: We will tolerate Brüning.
- @new_grand_coalition: We will try to form a new grand coalition.
- @new_elections: We will have new elections.
- @unity_government


@new_grand_coalition
title: A "New Grand Coalition" of all the constitutional parties?
subtitle: CCF + RPC + BVP + LPC + CPC + Others ([+ neo_weimar_coalition +]%)
view-if: neo_weimar_coalition >= 50 and grand_coalition < 50
choose-if: rpc_relation >= 50 and cpc_relation >= 30
unavailable-subtitle: CCF + RPC + BVP + LPC + CPC + Others ([+ neo_weimar_coalition +]%) - [? if rpc_relation < 50 : We do not have adequate relations with the Center Party. ?][? if cpc_relation < 30 : We do not have adequate relations with the CPC. ?]

How do we convince vehemently anti-socialist parties to allow us to form a majority coalition? Our largely benevolent relations with the Center and CPC may allow us some leverage.

- @use_resources
- @toleration_bruning: No. We will tolerate a minority government.
- @new_elections: No. We will have new elections.
- @unity_government

@use_resources
title: Use our resources to smooth over the creation of a coalition.
subtitle: -2 resources
unavailable-subtitle: Not enough resources (need 2).
choose-if: resources >= 2
on-arrival: resources -= 2; ccf_in_government = 1; in_grand_coalition = 1; left_dissent += 4;
achievement: constitutional_coalition

We transfer some of our campaign funds to our putative coalition partners. Some would call this corruption, but perhaps it is necessary to save our democracy.

Now, we have a new grand coalition, a "Constitutional Coalition" of all the non-fascist and non-communist parties. Leftists in our party are somewhat skeptical of this arrangement. 


Who should be chancellor?

- @join_bruning: For better or for worse, it must be Heinrich Brüning of the Center.
- @woodsworth_chancellor_new: J.S. Woodsworth for Chancellor?

@woodsworth_chancellor_new
subtitle: This will reduce our leverage in the ministries.
view-if: not historical_mode or not ccf_prussia
on-arrival: leverage -= 10; chancellor = "Woodsworth"; chancellor_party = "CCF"
go-to: ministries

We have assembled a new coalition under J.S. Woodsworth.


@unity_government
title: The Center Party offers a "Government of National Unity" under Chancellor Joseph Wirth.
subtitle: CCF + RPC + BVP + LPC + CPC + Others ([+ neo_weimar_coalition +]%)
view-if: rpc_party_leader == "Joos" and neo_weimar_coalition >= 50 and weimar_coalition < 50 and rpc_relation >= 10

The Center Party leader, Joseph Joos, clearly sees the threat from the ascension of the anti-democratic extremist parties, and thus tries to negotiate a "Government of National Unity" to save the republic. This coalition would be led by Joseph Wirth, a left-leaning member of the Center Party and former chancellor, and would encompass all of the constitutional parties. Our role in this government might be limited, however.

- @unity_government_2
- @reject_unity_government: No, we will not accept this offer.

@unity_government_2
title: Accept the offer!
on-arrival: chancellor = "Wirth"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; ccf_in_government = 1; in_grand_coalition = 1; in_unity_government = 1; leverage = 15; rpc_relation += 5; cpc_relation += 4
achievement: constitutional_coalition
go-to: ministries

We have formed a new unity government of all the constitutional parties! We have a limited choice in ministries for this government.


@reject_unity_government
on-arrival: rpc_relation -= 8; lpc_relation -= 5; cpc_relation -= 5

Our rejection of the unity government has hurt our relations with the bourgeois and center-right parties.

- @woodsworths_dilemma
- @toleration_bruning: We will tolerate a minority government led by Brüning.
- @toleration_wirth: We will tolerate a minority government led by Joseph Wirth.
- @new_elections: There will be new elections.


@toleration_wirth
view-if: rpc_party_leader = "Joos"
choose-if: king == "Woodsworth"
unavailable-subtitle: King George V will not support a minority government led by Joseph Wirth.
on-arrival: chancellor = "Wirth"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; ccf_in_government = 0; ccf_toleration = 1; rpc_relation += 5; foreign_minister_party = "CPC"; interior_minister_party = "RPC"; justice_minister_party = "I"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = lpc_name; finance_minister_party = "CPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "RPC"; pro_republic -= 2;

We have supported a minority government led by the Center Party under Chancellor Joseph Wirth.



@no_majority_papen
on-arrival: pro_republic -= 10; next_election_time = time+3; next_election_month = month + 3; next_election_year = year; next_election_year += 1 if next_election_month > 12; next_election_month -= 12 if next_election_month > 12; workers_nsdap += 6; unemployed_nsdap += 6; old_middle_nsdap += 5; new_middle_nsdap += 5; rural_nsdap += 5; no_majority_papen_elections += 1; workers_ccf -= 8 if pro_republic < 45; workers_ccf *= 0.85 if pro_republic < 40; workers_nsdap += 5 if pro_republic < 40;

After the elections, Papen is still deeply unpopular, without any hint of coalition support, and there is a vote of no confidence called against him almost immediately. No matter how we vote, the measure would pass. The Reichstag is dissolved once more.

New elections have been set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].


@no_majority_papen_2
on-arrival: chancellor = "Schleicher"; pro_republic -= 10; next_election_time = time+5; next_election_month = month + 5; next_election_year = year; next_election_year += 1 if next_election_month > 12; next_election_month -= 12 if next_election_month > 12; workers_nsdap += 5; unemployed_nsdap += 10; old_middle_nsdap += 5; new_middle_nsdap += 5; rural_nsdap += 10; workers_ccf -= 8 if pro_republic < 45; workers_ccf *= 0.85 if pro_republic < 40; workers_nsdap += 5 if pro_republic < 40; finance_minister_party = "I"; interior_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = "I"; labor_minister_party = "I"; foreign_minister_party = "I"; agriculture_minister_party = "I"; reichswehr_minister = "I";

There is no path to a majority government. George V is displeased with Papen, and calls on him to resign. Now, former army general Kurt von Schleicher has been appointed chancellor, again as part of a monarchial government.

Schleicher's government is deeply unpopular among all parties of the Reichstag. Despite his support for a coalition with the NSDAP, the Nazis want power all to themselves, without Schleicher.

New elections have been set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].


@no_majority_schleicher
