@grand_coalition
title: We can form a Grand Coalition.
view-if: grand_coalition >= 50 and grand_coalition_failed == 0
subtitle: CCF + RPC + BVP + LPC + CPC ([+ grand_coalition +]%)
on-arrival: in_grand_coalition = 1; in_popular_front = 0; in_left_front = 0
go-to: grand_coalition_ccf_lead if (n_elections <= 1 and largest_party == "CCF") or (largest_party == "CCF" and ccf_r >= 30) or king = "Woodsworth"; grand_coalition_rpc_lead if king != "Woodsworth" and ((n_elections > 1 and ccf_r < 30) or (n_elections <= 1 and largest_party != "CCF"))

# TODO: if there are enough votes to form a grand coalition, who leads? Does the CCF lead or does Brüning (RPC) lead? In reality this depended on George V's will, basically, which in turn depended on what his camarilla supported.
# In the first election, CCF always leads. In subsequent elections, if ccf_r >= 29 then CCF leads, otherwise RPC leads?

@grand_coalition_rpc_lead
go-to: grand_coalition_rpc_lead_2 if cpc_relation >= 30; grand_coalition_fail if cpc_relation < 30

There are enough votes to form a majority coalition consisting of the CCF, Center (RPC), Bavarian People's (BVP), Democratic (LPC), and People's (CPC) parties. Given our rather weak electoral performance, [? if ccf_no_confidence = 1 : and our previous vote of no confidence against the government, ?][? if no_confidence_against_ccf = 1 : and the vote of no confidence against us, ?] King George V has asked the Center Party to take the lead role in forming a government.

# TODO: if the CCF participated in bringing down the previous government via a vote-of-no-confidence, or if we were essentially removed from government by our coalition partners, we should be more reluctant to participate in a new government.

@grand_coalition_rpc_lead_2

The Center chancellor is likely to be Heinrich Brüning of the Center Party [? if chancellor = "Brüning" : again. ?][? if chancellor != "Brüning": . ?] He is known for his conservatism and sympathy for monarchism, being on the right wing of the Center. [? if austerity >= 2 : Due to the government's austerity policies, many of our members are reluctant to participate in this coalition again. Some support a "toleration" arrangement in which we will provide outside support to prevent the far-right from either entering government or calling a successful no-confidence vote. Others support entering into pure opposition, and letting the right do what it wishes. ?]

Brüning is not opposed to a coalition with us. Alternatively, we could enter a "toleration" agreement.

- @join_bruning: Join the Brüning coalition.
- @bruning_oppo: Join the opposition.
- @toleration_bruning: We will "tolerate" a minority Brüning government.
- @unity_government

@join_bruning
view-if: grand_coalition >= 50 or neo_weimar_coalition >= 50
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; ccf_toleration = 0; in_grand_coalition = 1; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; foreign_minister_party = "CPC"; interior_minister_party = "RPC"; justice_minister_party = "RPC"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = "RPC"; finance_minister_party = "RPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "RPC"; leverage = 25 if leverage >= 25;
go-to: ministries

Heinrich Brüning welcomes us into his new cabinet. Now, we have our pick of ministries.

@bruning_oppo
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 0; ccf_toleration = 0; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; foreign_minister_party = "CPC"; interior_minister_party = "RPC"; justice_minister_party = "RPC"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = "RPC"; finance_minister_party = "RPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "RPC"; grand_coalition_failed = 1

By refusing to join the grand coalition or tolerating it, we essentially throw the balance of government to the right wing. [? if right_coalition >= 50 : There are enough votes to form a right-wing coalition that includes the SCP. However, the SCP leader, Hugenberg, is opposed to a coalition with the "November criminals" of the Center Party. And of course, the NSDAP is not interested in coalition government. This means that there will not be enough votes to form a majority coalition. ?][? if right_coalition < 50 : There are not enough votes to form a right-wing coalition that includes the SCP, and they are not interested in joining in a coalition with the "November criminals" of the Center Party, anyhow. And of course, the NSDAP is not interested in coalition government. This means that there is no route to a majority coalition. ?]

If we do not at least "tolerate" the government, there will be new elections in a few months. In the meantime, the King and Chancellor may use the emergency powers granted by Article 48 of the constitution to essentially govern by decree. And it is not at all clear that we will do any better in the next election.

- @join_bruning: Join the Brüning coalition.
- @toleration_bruning: We will tolerate Brüning after all.
- @woodsworths_dilemma
- @new_elections: New elections, it is!


@new_elections
on-arrival: {!
Q.next_election_month = Q.month + 3;
Q.next_election_time = Q.time + 3;
if (Q.next_election_month > 12) {
    Q.next_election_month -= 12;
    Q.next_election_year = Q.year + 1;
} else {
    Q.next_election_year = Q.year;
}
if (Q.chancellor == "Brüning") {
    Q.rpc_relation -= 5;
    Q.cpc_relation -= 5;
}
Q.pro_republic -= 8;
Q.workers_ccf -= 5;
Q.new_middle_ccf -= 5;
Q.old_middle_ccf -= 5;
Q.rural_ccf -= 5;
Q.catholics_ccf -= 3;
Q.new_middle_cpc -= 8;
Q.old_middle_cpc -= 8;
Q.new_middle_lpc -= 5;
Q.old_middle_lpc -= 10;
Q.rural_scp -= 5;
Q.workers_nsdap += 5;
Q.old_middle_nsdap += 6;
Q.new_middle_nsdap += 6;
Q.rural_nsdap += 6;
Q.unemployed_nsdap += 5;
// Thresholds are kind of arbitrary - adjusted because of negative economic effects on pro_republic
if (Q.pro_republic < 45 && Q.pro_republic >= 36) {
    Q.workers_ccf -= 6;
}
if (Q.pro_republic < 36) {
    // TODO: if you pursue a consistently revolutionary course, you might avoid this? But you might also cause a coalition between Hitler and the Center.
    Q.rpc_relation -= 5;
    Q.cpc_relation -= 5;
    Q.workers_ccf *= 0.85;
    Q.unemployed_ccf -= 2;
    Q.new_middle_ccf -= 5;
    Q.old_middle_ccf -= 5;
    Q.rural_ccf -= 5;
    Q.catholics_ccf -= 3;
    Q.workers_nsdap += 8;
    Q.old_middle_nsdap += 8;
    Q.new_middle_nsdap += 8;
    Q.rural_nsdap += 8;
    Q.unemployed_nsdap += 8;   
}
if (Q.far_right_coalition >= 50) {
    Q.sa_strength += 100;
    Q.sh_strength += 100;
    Q.coup_progress += 3;
}
!}

There is no path to a workable Reichstag majority or minority government. The next elections are set for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].

The people's faith in democracy is shaken by this ordeal. Of course, the Nazis are exploiting the instability to claim that democracy is unworkable, and that Canada needs a strong leader.


@toleration_bruning
choose-if: neo_weimar_coalition >= 50
unavailable-subtitle: The parties supporting Brüning do not have a majority.
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 0; ccf_toleration = 1; minority_government = 1; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; foreign_minister_party = "CPC"; interior_minister_party = "RPC"; justice_minister_party = "I"; labor_minister_party = "RPC"; reichswehr_minister_party = "I"; economic_minister_party = lpc_name; finance_minister_party = "CPC"; agriculture_minister_party = "RPC"; pro_republic -= 4; new_middle_cpc -= 5; new_middle_lpc -= 5; old_middle_cpc -= 5; old_middle_lpc -= 5; old_middle_nsdap += 5; new_middle_nsdap += 5; rural_scp -= 5;

We have decided to tolerate Brüning's government. This means that we will vote against no-confidence votes to make sure they fail, but also that we will not be directly participating as ministers in the government. Thus, we can prevent a new election and stop the far right from entering government.

@grand_coalition_fail
on-arrival: grand_coalition_failed = 1

Unfortunately, the CPC and BVP are unwilling to enter into another coalition with the CCF, so the grand coalition is unable to be formed.

- @no_majority: Thus, there is no clear majority.
- @woodsworths_dilemma
- @right_coalition_2: Perhaps a right-wing coalition may form.
- @beg_cpc: Perhaps we could ask the CPC to change their minds?
- @unity_government
- @coalition_menu: What are the other governing arrangements?


@beg_cpc
view-if: cpc_relation >= 15
go-to: cpc_conservative if stresemann_dead == 1; cpc_majority if stresemann_dead == 0

@cpc_majority
go-to: join_bruning

Under the influence of Gustav Stresemann, the CPC agrees to allow us into the coalition, and so does the BVP.


@cpc_conservative

The CPC asks us to adhere to their conservative economic policies (that is, extreme austerity and labor discipline) in exchange for us joining the coalition.

- @beg_cpc_2: But they would not have a majority without the CCF! The SCP and NSDAP have no interest in participating in government.
- @no_majority: There is no chance that we would agree.
- @woodsworths_dilemma
- @coalition_menu: What are the other governing arrangements?


@beg_cpc_2
go-to: beg_cpc_succeed; beg_cpc_fail

We make the case that without the CCF, there is no parliamentary majority, given the SCP and NSDAP's hostility to constitutional government.

@beg_cpc_succeed
go-to: join_bruning

Somehow, we succeed in convincing them! We are now in a coalition.


@beg_cpc_fail
go-to: no_majority

As expected, the CPC is too set in their anti-democratic ways.



@grand_coalition_ccf_lead
on-arrival: leverage -= 15 if cpc_relation < 20

As expected, the CCF is the largest party, and this time, we are expected to take the lead role in the formation of the next government, including selecting the chancellor. King [+ king +] has asked us to form a majority coalition with the Center (RPC), Bavarian People's (BVP), Democratic (LPC), and People's (CPC) parties.

[? if cpc_relation < 20 : As our relation with the CPC is poor, they are demanding more minister posts in order to remain part of the coalition. ?]

Who should be the chancellor?

- @douglas
- @woodsworth
- @Coldwell
- @rpc_chancellor
- @rpc_chancellor_wirth
- @no_govt


@douglas
title: Tommy Douglas for Chancellor
view-if: douglas_dead = 0
subtitle: Douglas is popular within the party, and is the preferred candidate of the Center and other parties.
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; chancellor = "Douglas"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; in_grand_coalition = 1 if in_weimar_coalition == 0
go-to: ministries

Douglas's appointment as chancellor is approved by all our potential allies.

@Coldwell
title: Major James Coldwell for Chancellor
view-if: douglas_dead = 1
subtitle: Major James Coldwell is a party leader, but can he also be chancellor?
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; chancellor = "Coldwell"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; in_grand_coalition = 1 if in_weimar_coalition == 0
go-to: ministries

Major James Coldwell's appointment as chancellor is approved by our potential allies.

@woodsworth
title: J.S. Woodsworth for Chancellor
view-if: not historical_mode or not ccf_prussia
subtitle: Woodsworth is currently the Premier of Prussia, and is one of our most popular leaders. However, other parties may have qualms about concentrating too much power in one man.

The Center party has significant qualms about appointing Woodsworth as chancellor, given that he is already Premier of Prussia. They ask for either more cabinet positions, or for Woodsworth to resign his state government role. The latter is completely unacceptable.

- @douglas
- @coldwell
- @woodsworth_2: Let the Center have their cabinet positions.

@woodsworth_2
subtitle: J.S. Woodsworth will be Chancellor.
view-if: not historical_mode
on-arrival: ccf_in_government = 1; chancellor = "Woodsworth"; chancellor_party = "CCF"; leverage -= 10; in_grand_coalition = 1 if in_weimar_coalition == 0
go-to: ministries

We have promised to let the Center have more influence in the government in response to the appointment of Woodsworth as chancellor.


@rpc_chancellor
title: Let the Center Party have their chancellor.
subtitle: Heinrich Brüning will be chancellor. This is unexpected and will cause internal dissent, but may give us a better position in negotiating for other cabinet positions.
on-arrival: left_dissent += 5; center_dissent += 5; labor_dissent += 5; rpc_relation += 10; cpc_relation += 5; pcc_relation -= 5; in_grand_coalition = 1 if in_weimar_coalition == 0; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; ccf_in_government = 1; leverage += 5
go-to: ministries

This is highly unexpected, and many in the left and center of our party are criticizing this decision.

[? if year == 1928 : Since Wilhelm Marx resigned, Heinrich Brüning has been appointed chancellor. ?]
[? if year > 1928: Heinrich Brüning of the Center Party has been appointed chancellor. ?]

@rpc_chancellor_wirth
title: Let Joseph Wirth of the Center Party be chancellor.
view-if: rpc_party_leader == "Joos"
subtitle: Wirth is on the left wing of the Center Party. This may give us a better position in negotiating for other cabinet positions.
on-arrival: left_dissent += 2; rpc_relation += 6; lpc_relation += 3; pcc_relation -= 5; in_grand_coalition = 1 if in_weimar_coalition == 0; chancellor = "Wirth"; chancellor_party = "RPC"; ccf_in_government = 1; leverage += 5
go-to: ministries




@no_govt
title: We do not form the government.
subtitle: This will cause significant internal dissent, and will lead to increased distrust from the bourgeois parties.
on-arrival: reformist_dissent += 5; center_dissent += 5; labor_dissent += 5; neorevisionist_dissent += 5

Are we sure about not participating in government? This will cause significant internal dissent, and will lead to increased distrust from the bourgeois parties. Even debating this option causes internal backlash. In addition, it is possible that the bourgeois and right-wing parties will also be unable to form a coalition government, leading to a regime appointed by King [+ king +].

- @douglas
- @woodsworth
- @rpc_chancellor
- @no_govt_goals: Yes, we're sure.

@no_govt_goals

What are our goals here, exactly?

- @majority: We hope to reach a socialist majority in the next election.
- @trap: It is a trap to form a government now. We would be unable to accomplish our goals.
- @socialism: Revolutionary socialism is our goal.

@majority
go-to: no_govt_2

@trap
on-arrival: radicalization += 1
go-to: no_govt_2

@socialism
go-to: no_govt_2


@no_govt_2
on-arrival: reformist_dissent += 25; center_dissent += 10; labor_dissent += 25; neorevisionist_dissent += 25; in_weimar_coalition = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; chancellor = "Brüning" if chancellor == "Marx"; ccf_in_government = 0; grand_coalition_failed = 1
go-to: right_coalition_post_ccf if right_coalition >= 50 and king != "Woodsworth" and year < 1929; new_elections_ccf if (right_coalition < 50 or year >= 1929) and king != "Woodsworth"; woodsworths_dilemma if king == "Woodsworth"


@right_coalition_post_ccf
go-to: right_coalition_2

@new_elections_ccf
on-arrival: next_election_time = time+3; next_election_month = month + 3; next_election_year = year; next_election_year = year + 1 if next_election_month > 12; next_election_month = next_election_month - 12 if next_election_month > 12; new_middle_ccf -= 5; old_middle_ccf -= 5; workers_ccf -= 3; catholics_ccf -= 3; in_election = 1

Since the remaining bourgeois and right-wing parties cannot form a tolerable governing agreement, new elections have been called for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +]. The previous chancellor has resigned, and has been replaced by Heinrich Brüning, also of the Center Party, ruling as part of a monarchial cabinet. 

We are seen as responsible for the failure to form a government, and many of our middle-class and even some working-class supporters have deserted the party.


@ministries

We can pick from any number of ministries. Controlling a ministry allows us to directly effect policy in that area. [? if in_left_front : Any ministry that we do not take will be given to the PCC. ?] [? if in_left_front and reichswehr_minister_party == "PCC" : If the PCC controls the Reichswehr Ministry, the army will most likely revolt. ?]

- #mins_1928
- #drop_mins_1928

